<Layout title="Mino Ware: Japan's Most Versatile Pottery and Your Complete Buying Guide | Japan Souvenir">
    <Header currentPage="ceramics" />

    <!-- Hero Image -->
    <section class="relative h-[60vh] w-full overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute inset-0">
            <!-- PIXTA: 美濃焼コレクション画像 (購入後 /images/mino-ware-hero.jpg に置換) -->
            <img src="/images/mino-ware-hero.jpg"
                 alt="Traditional Mino Ware Collection"
                 class="w-full h-full object-cover">
            <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/40"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 right-0 p-8 md:p-16">
            <div class="container mx-auto">
                <span class="text-jp-clay text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.3em] uppercase mb-4 block">Ceramics</span>
                <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-serif text-white leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
                    Mino Ware: Japan's Most Versatile Pottery and Your Complete Buying Guide
                </h1>
                <p class="text-white/70 text-sm mt-4">February 15, 2024 · By Smith Ikue</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Article Content -->
    <article class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-jp-offwhite">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-6 max-w-3xl">
            <div class="prose prose-lg font-serif text-jp-gray leading-loose">

                <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed mb-8">
                    Chances are, you've already used Mino ware without knowing it. Over half of all ceramics produced in Japan come from the Mino region—and for good reason. This is pottery that seamlessly blends beauty, function, and everyday life.
                </p>

                <!-- Section 1 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">What is Mino Ware?</h2>

                <p class="mb-6">
                    <strong>Mino ware (美濃焼 / Mino-yaki)</strong> is pottery produced in the Mino region of Gifu Prefecture, with a history spanning over 1,300 years. Unlike other Japanese ceramics defined by a single style, Mino ware is celebrated for its incredible diversity—from rustic tea ceremony bowls to sleek modern tableware.
                </p>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
                    <ul class="list-none space-y-3 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Origin:</strong> 7th century (Nara period), flourished during the Momoyama period (16th century)</li>
                        <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Diverse styles—from earthy Shino to elegant Oribe</li>
                        <li><strong>Today:</strong> Produces over 50% of Japan's tableware—the nation's largest ceramic producer</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p class="text-jp-clay font-medium mt-4 text-sm italic">"The pottery that defines Japanese daily life."</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 2 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Why is Mino Ware Special?</h2>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">Born from Tea Culture</h3>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Mino ware's golden age arrived during the Momoyama period (1573-1603) when tea master <strong>Sen no Rikyū</strong> and his followers revolutionized the tea ceremony. They rejected the Chinese perfection that dominated tea culture and embraced a new aesthetic: <em>wabi-sabi</em>—finding beauty in imperfection.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Mino potters answered this call with bold, unconventional styles that shocked the tea world and changed Japanese ceramics forever.
                </p>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">Japan's Largest Ceramic Producer</h3>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Today, Mino ware accounts for <strong>over 50% of all ceramics made in Japan</strong>. From the bowls in your favorite ramen shop to the plates in high-end restaurants, Mino ware is everywhere. This isn't just tradition—it's the foundation of Japanese tableware.
                </p>

                <!-- Image -->
                <div class="my-12">
                    <!-- PIXTA: 志野茶碗 (購入後 /images/mino-shino-bowl.jpg に置換) -->
                    <img src="/images/mino-shino-bowl.jpg" alt="Mino Ware Tea Bowl in Shino Style" class="w-full rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center">A classic Shino-style tea bowl—the warm, milky glaze that revolutionized Japanese tea culture</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 3 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">The Classic Styles of Mino Ware</h2>

                <p class="mb-6">
                    Unlike other pottery regions known for a single style, Mino ware encompasses multiple distinct traditions. Understanding these styles is key to appreciating—and choosing—Mino ware:
                </p>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">① Shino (志野)</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
                    <p class="mb-4">Japan's first white-glazed pottery, developed in the late 16th century.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Thick, milky-white glaze with a soft, warm texture</li>
                        <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Small pinholes in the glaze, often with subtle orange "fire color" (hi-iro)</li>
                        <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Tea bowls, sake cups, decorative pieces</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">② Oribe (織部)</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
                    <p class="mb-4">Named after tea master Furuta Oribe, who championed bold, unconventional designs.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Distinctive green copper glaze, often combined with geometric patterns</li>
                        <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Intentionally warped shapes, avant-garde designs</li>
                        <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Serving dishes, plates, tea ceremony pieces</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">③ Ki-Seto (黄瀬戸)</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
                    <p class="mb-4">A soft yellow glaze that evokes autumn warmth.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Pale yellow with subtle brown or green accents</li>
                        <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> Delicate, understated elegance</li>
                        <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Small plates, incense containers, tea wares</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">④ Setoguro (瀬戸黒)</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
                    <p class="mb-4">Jet-black glaze achieved by removing the piece from the kiln while still hot.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Deep, glossy black</li>
                        <li><strong>Characteristics:</strong> The "black tea bowl" prized by tea masters</li>
                        <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Tea bowls, sake cups</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Image -->
                <div class="my-12">
                    <!-- PIXTA: 織部焼 (購入後 /images/mino-oribe.jpg に置換) -->
                    <img src="/images/mino-oribe.jpg" alt="Oribe Style Mino Ware with Green Glaze" class="w-full rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center">Oribe ware's signature green glaze and bold geometric patterns—400 years ahead of its time</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 4 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Mino Ware vs. Other Japanese Ceramics</h2>

                <p class="mb-6">
                    Wondering how Mino ware compares to other famous Japanese pottery? Here's a quick guide:
                </p>

                <div class="bg-jp-black text-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 pb-4 border-b border-gray-700">
                            <div><span class="text-jp-clay font-bold">Mino Ware</span></div>
                            <div class="md:col-span-2 text-sm text-gray-300">Diverse styles, practical everyday use, Japan's largest producer</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 pb-4 border-b border-gray-700">
                            <div><span class="text-jp-clay font-bold">Arita Ware</span></div>
                            <div class="md:col-span-2 text-sm text-gray-300">Fine porcelain, blue-and-white designs, elegant decoration</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 pb-4 border-b border-gray-700">
                            <div><span class="text-jp-clay font-bold">Bizen Ware</span></div>
                            <div class="md:col-span-2 text-sm text-gray-300">Unglazed stoneware, natural wood-ash effects, earthy aesthetics</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                            <div><span class="text-jp-clay font-bold">Mashiko Ware</span></div>
                            <div class="md:col-span-2 text-sm text-gray-300">Folk craft tradition, rustic charm, influenced by Mingei movement</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 5 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">How to Enjoy Mino Ware</h2>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">Everyday Use</h3>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Mino ware is made to be used—this is pottery for real life:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Rice bowls:</strong> The heart of Japanese meals</li>
                    <li><strong>Plates & dishes:</strong> Every size for every cuisine</li>
                    <li><strong>Mugs & cups:</strong> From morning coffee to evening tea</li>
                    <li><strong>Sake sets:</strong> Elevate your drinking experience</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">Special Occasions</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li>Tea ceremony (Shino and Setoguro bowls are highly prized)</li>
                    <li>Kaiseki dining (restaurant-quality serving pieces)</li>
                    <li>Gifts for weddings and housewarmings</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-jp-clay pl-6 my-8">
                    <p class="text-lg italic">"From everyday rice to special occasions—Mino does it all."</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 6 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Beginner's Guide: How to Choose Mino Ware</h2>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">1. Choose Your Style</h3>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Think about what resonates with you:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Shino:</strong> Warm, soft, rustic</li>
                    <li><strong>Oribe:</strong> Bold, artistic, conversation-starting</li>
                    <li><strong>Ki-Seto:</strong> Subtle, elegant, understated</li>
                    <li><strong>Modern Mino:</strong> Clean lines, contemporary aesthetics</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">2. Consider Practicality</h3>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Most modern Mino ware is designed for daily use:
                </p>
                <p class="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded text-center mb-6">
                    <em>"Is this dishwasher and microwave safe?"</em><br>
                    <span class="text-sm text-gray-500">食洗機・電子レンジは使えますか？<br>(Shokushenki / Denshi renji wa tsukaemasuka?)</span>
                </p>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">3. Price Guide</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
                    <ul class="list-none space-y-3 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Rice bowls:</strong> ¥1,000 – ¥3,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Plates (medium):</strong> ¥1,500 – ¥5,000</li>
                        <li><strong>Traditional tea bowls:</strong> ¥5,000 – ¥30,000+</li>
                        <li><strong>Artist/master pieces:</strong> ¥50,000 and up</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 7 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Where to Buy Mino Ware</h2>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">① In the Mino Region (Best Option)</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Toki City & Tajimi City:</strong> The heart of Mino ware production</li>
                    <li><strong>Pottery festivals:</strong> Held throughout the year with great deals</li>
                    <li><strong>Direct from kilns:</strong> Best prices and unique finds</li>
                </ul>

                <h4 class="text-lg font-serif text-jp-black mt-6 mb-4">Recommended Shops & Destinations:</h4>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6 space-y-4">
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Oribe Street (オリベストリート), Tajimi</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">A charming street lined with galleries, studios, and shops showcasing local Mino ware.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.oribe-street.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">oribe-street.com →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Mino Ware Wholesale Center (道の駅 志野・織部)</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Roadside station with massive selection at wholesale prices. Perfect for stocking up.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.michinoeki-shinooribe.jp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">michinoeki-shinooribe.jp →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Toki Premium Outlets</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Major brands and local kilns with outlet prices. Combines shopping with ceramics hunting.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.premiumoutlets.co.jp/en/toki/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">premiumoutlets.co.jp/toki →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Ichinokura (市之倉さかづき美術館)</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Sake cup museum with over 1,300 pieces. Attached shop sells beautiful cups.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.sakazuki.or.jp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">sakazuki.or.jp →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Image -->
                <div class="my-12">
                    <!-- PIXTA: 多治見の街並み (購入後 /images/mino-town.jpg に置換) -->
                    <img src="/images/mino-town.jpg" alt="Pottery Shopping Street in Mino Region" class="w-full rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center">Exploring the pottery streets of Tajimi—where tradition meets modern design</p>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">② In Major Japanese Cities</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6 space-y-4">
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Kappabashi Street (Tokyo)</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Tokyo's famous kitchenware district. Many shops carry Mino ware for professional and home use.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">D&Department (Various locations)</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Curated selection of regional crafts including quality Mino ware.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.d-department.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">d-department.com →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Tokyu Hands / Loft</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray">Lifestyle stores with modern Mino tableware at reasonable prices.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-8 mb-4">③ Online (International Shipping)</h3>
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6 space-y-4">
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">JCRAFTS.com</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Curated Japanese crafts with international shipping. Good Mino selection.</p>
                        <a href="https://jcrafts.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">jcrafts.com →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Toiro</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Specializes in Mino ware with excellent English support and worldwide shipping.</p>
                        <a href="https://toiro.shop/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">toiro.shop →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Musubi Kiln</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Wide selection of Japanese ceramics including many Mino pieces.</p>
                        <a href="https://musubikiln.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">musubikiln.com →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-jp-clay pl-6 my-8">
                    <p class="text-lg italic">"Mino is close to Nagoya—an easy day trip from the city."</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 8 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Experiences in the Mino Region</h2>

                <p class="mb-6">
                    Make your visit unforgettable with these hands-on experiences:
                </p>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-6 space-y-4">
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Mino Ware Museum (美濃焼ミュージアム)</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Comprehensive collection of historic and contemporary Mino ware. Pottery workshop available.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.minoyaki-museum.jp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">minoyaki-museum.jp →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Pottery Experience Studios</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Try your hand at the wheel or painting. Many studios in Tajimi and Toki offer workshops in English.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Tajimi Mosaic Tile Museum</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">A stunning building dedicated to the region's tile-making tradition. Architecture alone is worth the visit.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.mosaictile-museum.jp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">mosaictile-museum.jp →</a>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p class="font-bold">Gifu Prefecture Tourism</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray mb-1">Official tourism info for planning your Mino ware journey.</p>
                        <a href="https://www.kankou-gifu.jp/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-jp-clay text-sm hover:underline">kankou-gifu.jp →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-jp-clay pl-6 my-8">
                    <p class="text-lg italic">"Make your own—the best souvenir is the one you create."</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 9 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Who Should Buy Mino Ware?</h2>

                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
                    <p class="mb-4">Mino ware is perfect for you if:</p>
                    <ul class="list-none space-y-3 text-sm">
                        <li>✓ You want beautiful tableware for everyday meals</li>
                        <li>✓ You appreciate variety and want to mix different styles</li>
                        <li>✓ You're looking for quality at reasonable prices</li>
                        <li>✓ You love both traditional and modern Japanese aesthetics</li>
                        <li>✓ You want durable pieces that handle daily use</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Section 10 -->
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Conclusion: Mino Ware is Japan's Everyday Masterpiece</h2>

                <p class="mb-6">
                    Mino ware proves that beauty and function aren't opposites—they're partners. This is pottery that enhances your daily meals, elevates your tea moments, and brings the warmth of Japanese craft into your home.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    From the revolutionary tea bowls that changed Japanese aesthetics forever to the modern plates in Tokyo's finest restaurants, Mino ware has been serving Japan for 1,300 years. And it's ready to serve you too.
                </p>
                <p class="text-xl text-jp-black font-medium mt-8">
                    When you bring home Mino ware, you're not just buying dishes. You're bringing home a piece of Japan's daily life—made beautiful.
                </p>

                <div class="mt-16 p-8 bg-white border-l-4 border-jp-clay">
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-serif text-jp-black mb-4">Planning Your Visit</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm">
                        <strong>Major Pottery Festivals:</strong><br>
                        • Tajimi Ceramic Festival (多治見陶器まつり): April & October<br>
                        • Toki Mino Ware Festival (土岐美濃焼まつり): May<br><br>
                        <strong>Access:</strong> 30 minutes from Nagoya by JR train to Tajimi Station<br><br>
                        During festivals, prices are often 30-50% off. Arrive early for the best selection and bring a bag—you'll want to take more than you planned!
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Author Section -->
            <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
                <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray">
                    Written by <strong>Smith Ikue</strong> — A Japanese local sharing authentic souvenirs and the stories behind them.
                </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Navigation -->
            <div class="mt-12 flex justify-between items-center">
                <a href="/category/ceramics" class="text-sm tracking-widest hover:text-jp-clay transition-colors">
                    &larr; Back to Ceramics
                </a>
                <a href="/articles" class="text-sm tracking-widest hover:text-jp-indigo transition-colors">
